        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[Feature]: Channel Broker Phase 2B Telegram migration proof",
        "body": "## Maintainer TL;DR\n\nThis stack consolidates the recurring Telegram/Discord/Slack/WhatsApp/Signal/iMessage/etc. maintenance churn behind one Channel Broker contract. OpenClaw keeps the shared semantics that repeatedly regress across native channel plugins: sessions, allowlists, routing, /verbose, streaming policy, durable final sends, receipts, retries, and auditability. Broker providers own platform mechanics: bot APIs, bridge/device state, native ids, delivery quirks, and provider capabilities.\n\nThis PR proves Telegram topics can move through broker-owned target parsing without changing native Telegram defaults. It is intentionally an opt-in proof layer, not the default migration.\n\nThe direction is intentionally incremental: first land the versioned broker SDK/plugin foundation, then prove conformance, then prove opt-in routing for the major channels, then model long-tail and constrained providers. Only after migration paths exist should legacy native-channel feature work freeze in #86115.\n\n## Why This Is Better\n\nToday, one fix to streaming, /verbose, or delivery behavior can make Telegram fast this week and then break Discord, Slack, or another native plugin the next week. The broker path makes those shared semantics one OpenClaw-owned contract instead of many platform-specific re-implementations. When a provider adds support for previews, threads, receipts, media, or constrained account modes, that capability can become available through the same contract to routed channels whose provider declares and passes conformance for it.\n\n## Stack Shape\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n  U[\"Umbrella issue #86105: reduce maintained-channel churn\"] --> P1[\"#86096 Phase 1: SDK + bundled broker foundation\"]\n  P1 --> P2A[\"#86153 Phase 2A: conformance + signed inbound\"]\n  P2A --> P2B[\"#86154 Phase 2B: Telegram opt-in proof\"]\n  P2B --> P2C[\"#86156 Phase 2C: Discord opt-in proof\"]\n  P2C --> P2D[\"#86157 Phase 2D: Slack opt-in proof\"]\n  P2D --> P3[\"#86164 Phase 3: official/app capability matrix\"]\n  P3 --> P4[\"#86165 Phase 4: constrained provider capabilities\"]\n  P4 -. \"future, not in this stack\" .-> P5[\"Future freeze issue #86115: legacy native-plugin freeze\"]\n```\n\n| PR | Role in the consolidation |\n| --- | --- |\n| #86096 | Creates the versioned broker SDK/plugin foundation, provider routing guard, media final-send mapping, SecretRef/cancellation handling, and prefix-ownership contract. |\n| #86153 | Proves shared lifecycle conformance and adds signed inbound webhook registration/runtime handoff: inbound dedupe, durable final sends, receipts, retryable failures, preview/progress gates, and /verbose channelData. |\n| #86154 | Proves Telegram topics can route through broker targets without native Telegram internals. |\n| #86156 | Proves Discord DMs/channels/threads preserve conversation semantics through broker routing. |\n| #86157 | Proves Slack DMs/channel threads preserve direct/thread semantics through broker routing. |\n| #86164 | Adds official/app platform aliases, capability matrix rows, and declared delivery capability enforcement for long-tail channels. |\n| #86165 | Adds constrained-provider metadata for WhatsApp, Signal, iMessage, and bridge-backed providers. |\n\n## Ownership Model\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  Core[\"OpenClaw core<br/>sessions, routing, allowlists<br/>/verbose, streaming, retries<br/>receipts, audit\"] --> Broker[\"channel-broker plugin<br/>openclaw/plugin-sdk/channel-broker<br/>V1 protocol\"]\n  Broker --> Provider[\"Provider-owned broker<br/>HTTP/webhook transport<br/>platform adapters\"]\n  Provider --> Platforms[\"Telegram, Discord, Slack<br/>Teams, Matrix, WhatsApp<br/>Signal, iMessage, long tail\"]\n  Provider --> Broker\n  Broker --> Core\n```\n\n## Review Shape\n\nThese PRs are intentionally linear. GitHub still shows `main` as the base for each PR so maintainers can land them one by one from fork branches; the branches themselves are stacked, and maintainers can review the focused adjacent diffs here:\n\n| PR | Focused adjacent diff |\n| --- | --- |\n| #86153 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-protocol...feat/channel-broker-conformance |\n| #86154 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-conformance...feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing |\n| #86156 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing...feat/channel-broker-discord-routing |\n| #86157 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-discord-routing...feat/channel-broker-slack-routing |\n| #86164 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-slack-routing...feat/channel-broker-official-platform-capabilities |\n| #86165 | https://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-official-platform-capabilities...feat/channel-broker-constrained-platform-capabilities |\n\n## This PR\n\n- Phase: Phase 2B - Telegram opt-in broker routing proof\n- Role: Proves Telegram topics can route through broker targets without native Telegram internals.\n- Head: `9f4d3d7cc9`\n\n## Current Review State\n\nThis PR is live for maintainer review. Current head: `9f4d3d7cc9`.\n\nFocused local validation for this phase is documented below. Broad validation remains owned by GitHub Actions. Native channel defaults remain unchanged unless this phase explicitly says otherwise.\n\n## Summary\n\n- Adds the Phase 2B Telegram broker routing proof on top of #86153 and #86096.\n- Normalizes Telegram topic shorthand in the broker plugin, including `broker:telegram:<chat>:topic:<id>` and numeric `<chat>:<topic>` targets.\n- Canonicalizes outbound broker session routes to `telegram:<chat>?threadId=<id>` so topic routing is stable without importing native Telegram internals.\n\n## Rollout Context\n\nCloses #86110\nRelated #86108\nRelated #86105\nStacked on #86153\nStacked on #86096\nSupersedes closed PR #86137, which was closed by the repository active-PR cap rather than by an implementation failure.\n\nNative Telegram defaults stay unchanged. Existing target-prefix ownership still keeps `telegram:` owned by the native Telegram plugin when that plugin is installed; this PR proves the opt-in broker route through `broker:telegram:...` and the broker alias path when native Telegram is absent.\n\nFor review, the focused stack diff is:\nhttps://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-conformance...feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** Telegram topic targets can route through `channel-broker` and become provider requests with canonical `telegram` platform, channel conversation id, and topic `threadId`.\n- **Real environment tested:** Local OpenClaw checkout at `/Volumes/LEXAR/repos/openclaw-channel-broker`, using the Channel Broker plugin and SDK from the stacked rollout branch on May 24, 2026.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Ran a `node --import tsx --input-type=module` terminal proof that called `channelBrokerPlugin.message.send.text` with `to: \"broker:telegram:-1001234567890:topic:42\"` and captured the provider request passed to the configured broker runtime.\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal output excerpt from that local command:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"telegram-topic\",\n  \"messageId\": \"native-telegram-topic\",\n  \"platform\": \"telegram\",\n  \"conversation\": {\n    \"id\": \"-1001234567890\",\n    \"type\": \"channel\",\n    \"threadId\": \"42\"\n  },\n  \"requirements\": {\n    \"text\": true,\n    \"thread\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** The live plugin path normalized Telegram topic shorthand into the broker provider request shape without importing native Telegram extension internals.\n- **What was not tested:** Live Telegram Bot API traffic and the full local suite; this PR stays scoped to opt-in broker routing proof.\n\n### Behavior\n\nOpenClaw can route a Telegram topic through `channel-broker` without Telegram extension code. The broker receives a normalized platform `telegram`, conversation id, and thread id; OpenClaw keeps the session route canonical and leaves native Telegram prefix ownership intact.\n\n### Environment\n\n- Local checkout: `/Volumes/LEXAR/repos/openclaw-channel-broker`\n- Branch: `feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing`\n- Head: `9f4d3d7cc9` (current Telegram proof head)\n\n### Steps\n\n1. Sent a synthetic message to `broker:telegram:-1001234567890:topic:42` through `channelBrokerPlugin.message.send.text`.\n2. Verified the provider request used `platform: \"telegram\"`, `conversation.id: \"-1001234567890\"`, and `conversation.threadId: \"42\"`.\n3. Resolved the outbound session route for the same target.\n4. Verified the route canonicalized to `telegram:-1001234567890?threadId=42` and preserved channel chat semantics.\n\n### Evidence\n\n- `pnpm exec vitest run extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.test.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/conformance.test.ts --config test/vitest/vitest.extension-channel-broker.config.ts`\n  - 2 files passed, 10 tests passed.\n- `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit -p extensions/channel-broker/tsconfig.json`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check extensions/channel-broker/src/target.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.test.ts`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm exec oxlint extensions/channel-broker --format unix`\n  - passed.\n- `git diff --check`\n  - passed.\n\n### Observed Result\n\nTelegram topic routing is represented by broker-owned target normalization and provider request semantics, not by core importing or calling native Telegram extension internals.\n\n### Not Tested\n\n- Live Telegram Bot API traffic; this PR is the opt-in broker migration proof, not a live provider connector.\n- Full local suite. Per `/Volumes/LEXAR` policy, broad validation is left to GitHub Actions.\n\n## Current Stack Gate Context\n\nThis branch is rebased on the current Phase 1 foundation head. Focused local validation is documented above or below; broad validation remains on GitHub Actions.\n\n",
